<html>

<title>GOVERNMENT SHOULD NOT ENCOURAGE NEWEST HEROIN EPIDEMIC</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>GOVERNMENT SHOULD<br>
NOT ENCOURAGE<br>
NEWEST HEROIN EPIDEMIC</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Robert L. Maginnis</i></center>

<p>

We are about to repeat an epidemic among young people, according
to Ginna Marston, research director for the Partnership for a
Drug-Free America.  &quot;It's stupid, because an earlier generation
has already been through this,&quot; Marston said.

<p>

The Partnership has launched an advertising campaign to counteract
&quot;heroin chic&quot; in the pop culture.  Meanwhile, in July,
a White House panel of scientists and activists who serve as advisors
on AIDS policy labeled the administration &quot;timid&quot; for
failing to support drug-abuser needle-exchange programs. Of the
panel members, almost half have the AIDS virus and an equal number
are homosexual.

<p>

This panel, well-intentioned but misguided, is part of an organized
effort to secure government funding for clean needle giveaways
to drug addicts in an attempt to slow the spread of the AIDS virus.
The evidence that such giveaways work, however, is far from conclusive.

<p>

A 1993 law permits the government to use federal funds to support
exchanges only if they can be scientifically shown to slow the
spread of the AIDS virus without increasing drug abuse.  To date,
studies are plagued with problems.  They rely on self-reporting
by addicts, downplay sexual transmission of the AIDS virus, generally
ignore the impact on communities near exchange sites, trivialize
the drug problem and never measure HIV seroconversion rates, the
only true indication of effectiveness.

<p>

Two of the three medical doctors on a much-cited government needle
study say that needle exchanges &quot;are not the panacea their
supporters hope for.&quot;  Now is not the time for government to 
tacitly endorse drug abuse by giving needles to addicts.

<p>

Worldwide heroin production has nearly doubled since the late
1980s. Since 1988, emergency room &quot;episodes&quot; in the
U.S. resulting from heroin overdoses have increased
68 percent.  Street heroin purity is up from a low of 4 percent
a decade ago to nearly 70 percent today.  Meanwhile, competition
between Colombian cartels and Asian syndicates has driven the
street price for a glassine envelope of smack as low as five dollars.

<p>

Heroin's growing popularity stems from its low price and high
purity and the fact that needle-shy users can now get high from
snorting or smoking the substance.  A Yale University student
explains, &quot;Most people here are snorting dope. There's a
very safe-sex-style, safe-drug-use aesthetic.&quot;

<p>

Heroin is the drug of choice among many of today's rock stars.
In spite of the well-publicized July 12, 1996 heroin death of
rocker Jonathan Melvoin, a keyboard player for the Smashing Pumpkins,
abuse grows.  &quot;Heroin is hot,&quot; says Detective Frank
Lyga, with the Los Angeles Police Department's Hollywood narcotics
division.  The August 9 edition of <I>Entertainment Weekly</I>
says that &quot;heroin has become the cocaine of the '90s&quot;
and a recent article in <I>Rolling Stone</I> profiled heroin's
resurgence in colleges.

<p>

&quot;Heroin's huge because it's the most extreme thing,&quot;
says Danny Boyle, director of &quot;Trainspotting,&quot; a controversial
new movie about Scottish heroin abusers.  The movie portrays heroin
abuse as exciting and may seduce some into drug experimentation.

<p>

In the face of rising heroin abuse, drug czar General Barry McCaffrey
is unwilling to support pro-needle advocates and wants to fight
illegal drug abuse.  &quot;The problem is not dirty needles,&quot;
says McCaffrey, &quot;the problem is heroin addiction.&quot;
Others agree.

<p>

&quot;Our goal should be to eliminate drug abuse,&quot; says Rep.
Charles Rangel (D-N.Y.), &quot;not to find a cleaner, safer way
to do it.&quot;  Dr. James Curtis, director of the Department
of Psychiatry, Harlem Hospital Center, says exchanges are &quot;poor
medicine&quot; and &quot;promote a breakdown in law and order.&quot;

<p>

Philip Lee, assistant Secretary of Health and Human Services and
a former needle exchange researcher, suggests exchanges &quot;may
send a mixed message about drug use.&quot;  Eighty-six exchanges
now operate in 55 U.S. cities without federal funds.  They provide
free drug-injecting supplies, condoms, advice on shooting drugs
properly, warnings about bad heroin, and counseling that sometimes
leads to treatment.

<p>

Although the science is inconclusive, expect AIDS activists and
pro-drug legalization forces (who never shy away from using incomplete
or erroneous data to support their agenda) to pressure the government
to approve funds for needle giveaways.  To endorse
one evil in an attempt to prevent another is at best a no-win
situation.  Clearly, this could become another example of an expensive
government program working at cross purposes to sound public policy.

<p>

-- 9/9/96

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Robert Maginnis is a senior policy analyst with the Family
Research Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research and educational
organization.</i>

<p>

