<title>A HIGHER PRO-LIFE TEST</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>A HIGHER PRO-LIFE TEST</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Gary L. Bauer</i></center>

<p>

Marvin Olasky's &quot;stricter&quot; pro-life litmus test (<I>World</I>, 
November 11, 1995) moved me to respond.  Few Christians have
done more to advance the pro-life cause than Dr. Olasky.  I honor
his spiritual commitment, his deep scholarship and his passion
for unborn children.  I am grateful, especially, for Marvin and
Susan's cross-racial adoption of a young son.  As the son of an
adopted father, I thank the Lord for their good hearts.

<p>

Still, I must dissent, because I do not believe that my friend's
formulation advances the effort to protect innocent, unborn children.
While I fully agree that we should ask those who would govern
us to go <I>beyond</I> mere formal and legalistic support for
a Human Life Amendment, we must insist that they go <I>at least
that far.</I> We have heard similar arguments by pro-life leaders
that we might be better off with a &quot;culturally conservative&quot;
president, one who speaks out for abstinence and for personal
responsibility than with a leader who gives mere &quot;lip service&quot;
to the <I>chimera</I> of a Human Life Amendment.

<p>

This, regrettably, is the logical fallacy of the false dilemma.
We have never sought insincere pro-life leadership.  We fully
understand that only those who are themselves convinced are likely
to be convincing to others.  But if we abandon a <I>higher test</I>
for pro-life support, we risk losing everything we have sought
in public policy.

<p>

What is that higher test?  It can be stated simply.  Lincoln said
that God gave man a hand and a mouth.  &quot;And his hand has
a right to bring bread to his mouth without controversy.&quot;
This simple and eloquent statement provided the philosophical
foundation for the Emancipator's opposition to slavery.  Examined
closely, it also provides the platform for Christian opposition
to abortion.

<p>

God forms the child in the womb.  He forms her lungs and her lips.
Her lungs have a right to draw past her lips the air He has so
graciously provided <I>without controversy.</I> Lincoln knew
that &quot;if slavery was not wrong, then nothing is wrong.&quot;
We know that if abortion is not wrong, then nothing is wrong.

<p>

This nation cannot survive as a political community if we turn
our back on this fundamental principle of right and wrong.  Some
<I>in society</I> will carry the burden of all private means to
provide alternatives to abortion.  They deserve the honor and
gratitude of the Ages. They tend the moral lights around us.
They shield the flame of conscience.

<p>

But what we need from those <I>in public office</I> is an understanding
of why government exists. Jefferson said that &quot;the care
of  human life and happiness <I>and not their destruction</I>
is the first and only legitimate object of good government [emphasis
added].&quot;  It was this understanding that infused our Declaration
of Independence. It was this understanding that Lincoln expressed
so convincingly in his Gettysburg Address. Lose that understanding
and we lose America.

<p>

What is at stake is not just the millions of human lives that
will be sacrificed if we abandon our commitment to the constitutional
protection of innocent human life. These lives are precious and
irreplaceable.  We pro-lifers must stand as well for the continued
life of this land we love.  Pope John Paul II put Lincoln's immortal
words at Gettysburg in the form of a question: &quot;Can any
nation so conceived and so dedicated long endure?&quot;  America
cannot survive the death of her spirit.

<p>

Surely, we need to create a pro-life culture.  Just as surely,
it is cruel and unjust <I>court rulings</I> which prevent Americans
from expressing those pro-life convictions they already hold.
How else can we explain the deplorable action of the Supreme
Court in striking down the abortion laws of 50 states?  How else
can we explain inferior courts' contemptuous sweeping away of
a host of protective laws passed since the <I>Webster</I> decision
of 1989?  It is these <I>political bodies</I> which are strangling
pro-life culture in a back alley.

<p>

Dr. King certainly shared the goal of a just society in which
no one would be judged by the color or his skin, but by &quot;the
content of his character.&quot;  Yet, that cultural goal never
diverted him from supporting timely political action against lynching.
&quot;I know a law cannot make a white racist love me,&quot;
he said, &quot;but the chances are much better that he will <I>learn</I> 
to love me if he hasn't lynched me first!&quot;

<p>

Imagine you are seated next to the president of the United States
and that the two of you are forced to witness a partial-birth
abortion.  Imagine further that he is the only one in the world
with power to stop the abortionist from jamming his scissors into
the base of the little girl's skull.  Do you want a &quot;culturally
conservative&quot; but &quot;pro-choice&quot; president to be
in that room with you?  Or do you want a president who believes
that it is morally and constitutionally wrong to take that little
girl's life?

<p>

So let's petition all those who would have power over us.  Let's
remind them of their duty to defend innocent human life.  We must
call them to a higher test -- support for a Human Life Amendment. Let's 
honor all those who are giving practical and loving support to women 
who choose life.  But let's give power only to those who understand that 
they have no authority unless it comes from above.

<p>

-- 10/17/96

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Gary L. Bauer is president of the Family Research Council in 
Washington, D.C.</i>

<p>

<center>
