<html>

<title>A BURNING NEED FOR RECONCILIATION</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>A BURNING NEED FOR<br>
RECONCILIATION</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Robert L. Maginnis</i></center>

<p>

In the last 14 months, 19 black churches in the South have been
torched, and federal authorities have ample evidence that racism
is the motivation.

<p>

Americans of all races must reject such bigotry.  Reconciliation
must begin with the same institution that brought about racial
healing in the 1960s, the church.  A hint of how this might happen
occurred during a mass rally recently in the Georgia Dome.

<p>

On February 13-15, approximately 43,000 pastors met in the Georgia
Dome to remove the barriers of racism and denominationalism. 
Pastors of all races gathered to worship and be encouraged.  Bishop
Wellington Boone, a black pastor, told how the black community
often finds fault with itself, so much so that there hasn't been
spiritual renewal in the black community for more than 100 years.

<p>

Dr. Raleigh Washington said that the black community is wrapped
up in past problems that affect the present and future life. 
Following Washington's presentation, Dr. Jack Hayford, a white
pastor, spoke and asked all African-American, Indian, Hispanic
and Asian pastors to forgive the white man for how he has hurt
and offended them in the past.  It was a dramatic time as he asked
for forgiveness on behalf of all whites.

<p>

Later, Promise Keeper founder and former University of Colorado
football coach Bill McCartney urged church leaders to commit themselves
to racial reconciliation.

<p>

Although there has been some progress in racial reconciliation
since the 1960s, there are still serious, lingering examples of
racial division.  Two months ago, arson destroyed a black church
in Knoxville, Tennessee.  This was the fifth black church in Tennessee
to burn in 13 months. The church's charred remains revealed 
spray-painted, racist graffiti. After the church burning, a racist 
letter was circulated promising that if interracial relationships 
continued, white supremacists would embark on a reign of terror.

<p>

Dewey Roberts, the president of the Knoxville chapter of the NAACP
blames &quot;a strong racist element within the community,&quot;
the <I>Boston Globe</I> reported.  One of the pastors of the burned
Knoxville church, Rev. Jerry Upton observed, &quot;None of us
want to believe that this can happen in America in 1996.&quot;

<p>

That church burning wasn't Knoxville's only racially-motivated
incident.  There was an unsolved cross-burning last year.  Additionally,
in another part of Tennessee this month, three white men will
be sentenced under federal civil rights law for burning two black
churches a year ago.

<p>

Meanwhile, two black churches were destroyed in west Alabama.
The publisher of a west Alabama weekly newspaper,  John Zippert,
told the <I>New York Times</I>, &quot;I don't think any of this
was accidental.  I think these particular churches were targeted.
You have white churches in between all of them that were not
touched.&quot;

<p>

Morris Dees, the head of the Southern Poverty Law Center in Montgomery,
a nonprofit agency that tracks hate groups and tries to promote
racial harmony, dismissed Zippert's explanation.  This area in
Alabama is not where white supremacist groups thrive.  He suggested,
&quot;This is deer hunting season and you have a lot of hunting
clubs up there, and a lot of drunk white boys who might be angry
at not getting a deer,&quot; the <I>Times</I> reported.

<p>

According to the <I>USA Today</I> report, of the 19 church burning
incidents since January 1995, seven occurred in the last two months
in seven different states: North and South Carolina, Georgia,
Alabama, Tennessee, Louisiana, and Mississippi.

<p>

These church burnings have drawn national attention.  NAACP Washington
Bureau director Wade Henderson urged Attorney General Janet Reno
to initiate an inquiry into the circumstances surrounding the
burned churches.  In a letter to Reno at the end of January 1996,
Henderson wrote, &quot;There appears to be a discernible pattern
which links the fires including the surprisingly large number,
and the fact that they have occurred at small, predominately black
churches in small communities.&quot;

<p>

Reno says she is investigating the fires to determine whether
they were racially motivated.  The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms is studying the incidents to determine whether there
is any organized and conspiratorial ring traveling from state
to state.

<p>

Meanwhile, seven Christian-based groups wrote Senator Orrin Hatch
and Congressman Henry Hyde, chairmen of the Congressional Judiciary
Committees, urging them to hold &quot;prompt hearings on the wave
of arson and other attacks on churches and church properties across
the United States.&quot;

<p>

Whether there is an organized conspiracy or these events are just
copycat incidents, they evince an unhealthy racial division. 
There must be healing and the church is central to the issue.

<p>

Just as the black church led the way in the 1960s, today's church
leaders of every color must answer the call and commit to healing
the wounds of racism that divide us.

<p>
-- 3/22/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Robert Maginnis is a senior policy analyst with the Family
Research Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research and educational
organization.</i>

<p>

<center>
