</DOCHDR>
<html>

<title>THE EMPIRE STRIKES BACK</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>THE EMPIRE STRIKES BACK</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Melissa Wells-Petry</i></center>

<p>

So much for democracy.  In its most recent foray into the culture
war, the Supreme Court held that it really could not think of
any good reason why the people of Colorado (or any other state,
for that matter) might think it wise to put the brakes on the
radical homosexual agenda by adopting Amendment 2, a law that
precludes special legal status for homosexuality.

<p>

Since the Supremes personally could not think of any good reason
for the law, they held there could be no good reason.  In fact,
they went further and charged that anyone who disagrees with them
is a bigot, a kook, and certainly a person who ought to be ashamed
of himself for even thinking of using the lowly democratic process
to express a view unacceptable to the ruling elite.  How dare
we, the people.

<p>

Not to put too fine a point on it, but are we sick of this already?
By that I mean that sick, helpless feeling in your stomach when
you know something right has been deemed, by the self-anointed,
&quot;wrong.&quot;  That ominous sickness that grips the heart
when it seems no matter how hard we try to take steps to address
the glaring problems in our society --whether it is to oppose
homosexuality, the transmogrification of marriage, the right to
infanticide (which surely the partial-birth abortion is) -- there,
like the Angel of Death, await the Elite who, with the stroke
of a pen, not only veto the result of our reasoning together through
the legislative process, but who also dash our aspirations for
building up, not tearing down, mores that are the essential supports
for civilization.  <I>We must fight back</I>.

<p>

As Americans, we have a deep respect for the rule of law.  But
for too long in this country, long after there ceased to exist
any evidence for doing so, we have equated the rule of law with
the rulings of the Supreme Court.  That equation is both incorrect
and dangerous.

<p>

If the Supreme Court succeeds in taking away our democracy, it
will be only because we let it.  The Court's recent opinion in
<I>Romer v. Evans</I>, which struck down Colorado's constitutional 
amendment on homosexuality, like <I>Roe v. Wade</I>, like countless 
other decisions that were nothing less than a raw power grab dressed 
up in fancy legal mumbo-jumbo, should be a call to arms in the culture 
war.

<p>

Instead of wailing about the excesses of these mere mortals in
robes, instead of being cowed by potential litigation, instead
of being silenced by the possibility that the justices might think
they know better than the people, for example, on what constitutes
a rationale response to the homosexual agenda, instead of saying
&quot;well, the Supreme Court says abortion is 'A-OK' and we can't
do anything about it,&quot; it's time to remind ourselves the
Constitution gives the people the real power, too, and the people
need to use it.

<p>

So the Supreme Court has called the 813,966 citizens who supported
Amendment 2 bigots.  So the Supreme Court has struck down the
law because it sees no danger in the State giving its imprimatur
to homosexuality and it won't credit those who do.  For those
who believe this nation must take steps to shore up its moral
foundation if it is to survive, and who conclude that special
legal status for homosexuality is inconsistent with that moral
foundation, the response must be to pass another law.  And another
law and another.  Pass one every week.  Change the language, take
a new approach, come at the problem from a different angle, don't
give up.  If the Supreme Court strikes it down, say &quot;Fine.
It is on your head.&quot;  Then dust yourself off and pass another
law.

<p>

Those who understand, in the words of Justice Scalia, that it
is &quot;eminently reasonable to use the legislative process to
address the various battles in the culture war may never get the
Court to admit the arrogance of its ways. (If <I>Roe</I> is any
object lesson, once the Court digs a whole, that hole only gets
deeper and more labyrinthine each time the justices heft the shovel.)

<p>

Nevertheless, if those who appreciate the legislative power the
Constitution gives to ordinary folks keep at it, one way or another,
eventually they will make their point.  At the end of the day,
they will be standing.  They will have exercised their prerogatives,
the prerogatives of democracy.  Never mind the elites.  The process
itself is a valuable vehicle through which to engage the soul
of the nation and through which to reason together (no matter
how contentiously) on the direction we, as a people, should go.

<p>

It's not pleasant to be labeled a bigot by the court -- especially
this nation's highest court -- simply because it is looking for a 
legal justification in all the wrong places. Be that as it may, the 
plain truth remains. The justices can rule all day that the people don't 
have the power to express their moral consensus at the ballot box on any
number of issues, but they can't diminish democracy unless we
let them.  Dish it up and send it back.  That's the response befitting
a government of, by, and for the people.

<p>
-- 5/23/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Melissa Wells-Petry is counsel to the Military Readiness Project
for the Family Research Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research
and educational organization.</i>

<p>

<center>
