<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>

<img align="left" alt="Photo of Paul Weyrich"
hspace=8 src="/townhall/columnists/weyrich.gif">
<img src="dateline.gif">
<br>[ <a href="/townhall/">Town Hall</a> | <a href="/townhall/columnists/weyrich/i-date.html">Previous Commentaries</a> | <a href="/townhall/columnists/">Columnists</a> ] 
</center>

 



<!a href="/townhall/columnists/weyrich.html"><!Biography>

<p>


<h3>
June 3, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
Phony Jurist Takes Reporters for a Ride
</h2>
<P>
<P>On Friday morning I was driving to the NET offices when ABC radio news, at 9 a.m. Eastern, broadcast that one of the jurors in the Whitewater case in Little Rock had said she had read about the defendants before the trial and had a negative impression of them. What happened at the trial confirmed that view.<P>
I was stunned. If that statement were true, it meant big time trouble for prosecutor Ken Starr. Subsequently I heard the same story on another radio network and on CNN. I asked a couple of attorneys for their opinion and they told me that if such a juror had indeed come forward, it meant that the defense had solid grounds to get the convictions overturned.<P>
As viewers of "Paul Talk" know, we discussed this story on the show. Others had heard the same story and called in to ask questions. One viewer raised the possibility that perhaps this had been a planted juror  not an unreasonable suggestion under the circumstances. As I answered the questions I was thinking that the Clintons must be the luckiest people on the face of the earth and such a development, if true, could effect the plans of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr to move forward on other cases.<P>
Friday night I was preoccupied with the wedding rehearsal dinner of my son, Steve, so I really didnt  pay close attention to newscasts, although I did hear one or two. On early Saturday morning when our two Washington papers arrived, I expected to see this story on the front page. Perhaps it would be a banner headline in the Washington Post. I was puzzled when I saw nothing about it but the wedding was a few hours away and our household was preoccupied with other thoughts. Again, with the reception going on into late evening, I didnt pay much attention to newscasts.<P>
When the Sunday papers arrived and I saw nothing of this story I knew there was something wrong. The Post, as a matter of fact, ran a four page spread, not including the beginning of the story on page one, to the effect that Hillary Clinton may now be in real trouble because her public statements do not match the facts in the Whitewater case. I dont remember pages of coverage like this in the Post since Watergate.<P>
In any case, I began to search for the story of what happened to the juror. I listened to radio newscasts. I heard nothing. Finally, after church and before leaving home for a graduation party, there was the story on CNNs Headline News, almost all the way through the news segment.<P>
It seems that the prejudicial statement which had been printed in the newspapers about the Whitewater trial was made not by an actual juror but by a woman of the same name as one of the jurors. The media kept hounding this woman, insisting that she was the real juror, despite her protestations that she was not. Finally, she became annoyed that they didnt believe her and she decided to go along with their demands for a statement. That was when she said what was quoted on the various newscasts which I had heard. <P>
In short, the so called mainstream media had been had. I picked up my information from them which resulted in my comments on Fridays show. I did add the caveat that my predictions would be true IF the woman had been quoted accurately. Nevertheless, I accepted as true what they had broadcast. So my apologies to all the viewers of "Direct Line" who went about their week-end thinking that the Whitewater convictions would be overturned and that even Governor Tucker might not resign the governorship of Arkansas after all.<P>
What of the responsibility of the networks, who promoted this story, to broadcast the fact that they had been had on their same newscasts? Although I was preoccupied, I did hear several newscasts on Saturday as we were going to and from the church and the reception and back home. But I heard not a word about this from the same news organizations which had made the story a big deal the day before.<P>
What of the newspapers which were giving extensive coverage to Whitewater? Why was there not a word that the electronic media had been taken? An attorney I discussed this case with at last nights graduation party told me that the real juror would probably have a good slander case against the media which broadcast information, damaging to her reputation, when they were quoting someone else. The real juror, so far as I know, has made no comment. Maybe she is busy talking to her lawyers.<P>
Someone ought to hold the broadcast news organizations accountable for what they did. That includes NET. None of us checked ourselves to determine if, in fact, a juror had made this statement before we broadcast it. It was the height of irresponsibility for them to have broadcast what they did and it was, frankly, irresponsible of me to have just repeated it without a call to Ken Starrs office to verify the story. The only thing I can say in our defense is that we dont have the huge news departments that the other networks have, and I, unfortunately, have almost no time to prepare for my show since I do this as a sideline, second to my duties as the CEO of NET as well as the CEO of the Free Congress Foundation.<P>
I hope all of us involved have learned a lesson about old fashioned journalism. Verify your story before airing it. I should not have assumed that because I had heard the story on three networks it was gospel. For that I profoundly apologize to my viewers. You deserved better. And all I can promise is that I will do my best to see that we dont repeat the same mistake again. Thats all for Direct Line for tonight.<P>


<blockquote>
<p>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote>   
