<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
April 30, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Defending Caesar Against God"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>

<P>
The Capitol today is filled with believers who are praying for their country. Although the "Washington for Jesus" rally did not live up to the crowd expectations of its promoters, it is nevertheless impressive to see that thousands of people are willing to take time off to come to their nation's capital to ask God's blessing on this land. 
<P>Indeed, it will take the intervention of the Almighty if this nation is going to reverse its course. Yesterday's hearings on assisted suicide, chaired by Rep. Charles Canady of (R-FL), pointed to another tragedy for the nation which is coming at us with thunderous speed. Yet hardly a whimper is heard about it from the nation's religious leaders. <P>
Saving this nation will be up to ordinary people. History is replete with examples of religious leaders who were either silent in the face of great moral crises or who actually cooperated with those inflicting moral crimes on the nation. I am not indicting all religious leaders here. There were a few leaders who did stand up to be counted at the moment of truth and there are some today. But usually those leaders are bucking the trend.<P>
Yesterday some 30 so-called religious leaders from Protestant and Jewish denominations sent President Clinton a letter backing him on the partial birth abortion veto. They wanted to give the President cover for one of the worst decisions ever made by an American President. Clinton's decision even earned him a particular denunciation by the Pope, something which almost never happens. But these Church leaders, including the presiding Bishop of the Episcopal Church, have seen fit to tell the President he was right in vetoing the bill. They defend Caesar against God.
<P>White House staffers say that the President has actually profited from his stand. The latest Gallop poll, taken after the President's veto, shows that Bill Clinton is leading Bob Dole by the largest margin ever, 58% to 36%. Thus, they claim, the President has done the right thing because the people back him. 
<P>Well, as I said, the ordinary folks, including the generation-X contingent who raised their hands in prayer on the mall today, are the people who will help turn this nation around. They are speaking out against the moral outrages of our time. The "Washington For Jesus" rally held a mock trial with secular society and its deadly sins as defendants. One of the teenagers wore a T-shirt which read, "I fear no evil because He is with me." Indeed, it is evil which stalks the land.
<P>When a six-year-old boy kills a two-month-old child, it is the product of evil. Yet in our time, we scarcely acknowledge evil. In fact, we attempt to turn evil into good. A new movie called "The Craft" attempts to glorify witchcraft. One of the stars of this movie says that all she is trying to do is to show that there is power all around us of which we are unaware. Yes, the power of death. All of these events happening in todays society have something in common. They are all a part of the ancient struggle between life and death. This struggle dates back to when God put man on earth.
<P>Today, however, death has more advocates. Death has the apologists. Death, whether by killing the unborn, or killing the terminally ill, or killing innocent bystanders with guns, or seducing the innocent through witchcraft, or by a thousand other means, death is triumphing over life in contemporary society. But God is life. So what the cult of death really translates to is a rejection of God. 
<P>Don't expect this nation's government or religious leaders to give the principle of life the upper hand. That will depend on the prayers of not only those who could show up in Washington today, but the prayers of all believers, of all faiths, wherever they are in this nation.  In the end it will depend on those who are willing to stand up and intone that ancient refrain, "Choose Life. Choose Life."<P>

<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
