<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
April 23, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Liberal Media Bias"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>
<P>
Speaker Newt Gingrich said yesterday that if the news media really believes so much in affirmative action, they should hire conservative Republicans. Gingrich was reacting to a Freedom Forum study, released by the Gannett-sponsored organization last week, which demonstrates that reporters covering politics and government are predominately liberal. 92% voted for President Clinton, as compared with 43% of the population as a whole. 
<P>
The study reveals something else, however, which is in my view, even more disturbing. It highlights the overwhelming cynicism of the national media toward anyone serving in office. This cynicism is especially pronounced, no doubt, when reporters cover politicians with whom they disagree.
<P>When I worked in the newsroom of a major metropolitan daily during the 1964 Presidential campaign, the reporters were overwhelmingly for the re-election of Lyndon Johnson. In fact, out of a staff of close to 100, I found only four supporters of the Republican nominee, Barry Goldwater. Editorially, the itself supported Goldwater, but the reporters who covered the campaign were against him. <P>

I have to say that, by and large, the professionalism of this group of reporters overcame their bias. Goldwater got fair coverage from the Milwaukee Sentinel despite the views of the reporters covering him.  When President Eisenhower got such a thunderous ovation at the 1964 GOP convention in San Francisco for criticizing the media, he was referring to columnists and editorial writers, not news reporters. Eisenhower suggested that lots of people were giving advice to the Republicans -- pundits who would, themselves, never vote for Republican candidates. The delegates roared their approval. 
<P>Today, the situation is reversed. In most papers the majority of columnists are from the center-right point of view. Even dedicated liberal papers such as the Washington Post and the New York Times have conservative columnists. Where those who believe in limited government, free enterprise, a strong national defense and traditional moral values take it on the chin is on the reportorial side of the equation. The people who cover the news are no longer taught, as they were when I was a reporter, that their personal opinions are not to show up in their reporting. <P>

The change came during Watergate. Prior to that time, there had been a small group of advocacy journalists who had made their way into America's newsrooms. They were in conflict with the traditional journalists who believed that their responsibility was to cover news, not to make news. When the Washington Post brought down the Nixon Administration, the advocacy journalists had won the day. Traditional journalists could no longer prevail because what the advocacy journalists had accomplished was to make the media a fourth and most powerful branch of government. 
<P>From that time to the present, the cynicism of journalists, many of whom do not hide their point of view, is overwhelming. They begin with the presumption that politicians, especially ones with whom they disagree, are guilty. All that remains is for them to identify the wrong the politicians have done. 
<P>
It is inconceivable, in the minds of these reporters, that the freshmen Republicans who got elected in 1994 actually believe in something and want the country to change. Rather, the reporters believe these freshmen have to be serving some special interests. They must be fronting for big money. Or at the very least they are serving their own interests. 
<P>It is not only a liberal bias, but this cynicism, which makes for the sort of coverage that has caused Speaker Gingrich to tell supporters that over the next six months they must become "personal radio stations" to overcome the bias of the media. The preference for liberal and Democratic politicians was in the newsrooms more than 30 years ago. What is different between now and then is that editors back then insisted that personal views be kept out of the news pages. This didn't always happen, of course, but the bias was subdued. Today the bias is blatant. 
<P>The only cure for this in the long run is the market place. Newspapers are in a state of steep decline. Each time new ratings come out, network television has lost some additional viewers to rival cable or direct broadcast channels. At some point, the owners of these media properties will stop being in a state of denial and will begin to examine their coverage. It is then that they may insist once again that advocacy journalism is for opinion columns and commentaries. 
<P>So when reading newspaper coverage makes you so angry you can't see straight, or when watching television news makes you want to smash the set, contribute to the growing market forces which will change the system. Don't buy the paper. And turn off that channel. There are other sources of news. The more you patronize the other sources instead of the ones which distort reality, the sooner the owners of the so-called mainstream media will be forced, for their own economic well being, either to change things or get out of the business.<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
