<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
April 29, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
Revolution?
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>
<P>
Last year at this time the new Leadership in the House of Representatives spoke boldly of "revolution." Speaker Gingrich especially insisted that business-as-usual was out; fundamental changes in the way that Washington does business were in. When some of us suggested that the Senate and President Clinton were unlikely to go along with such changes, House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bob Livingston retorted, "President Clinton is irrelevant and the Senate doesn't matter. Not one dime can be spent on a single program unless the House of Representatives okays the spending." Known as the One-House Veto strategy, this was the way Republicans were going to force an end to programs which they considered bad for the country.
<P>What a difference a year makes. Speaker Gingrich may have fun cavorting with Jay Leno or acting as substitute host for "Larry King Live," but these days there is no talk of revolution. The rest of the Republican Leadership tries to put a happy face on what happened with the budget process, but it is hard for them to do. As for Chairman Livingston, he doesn't much like to answer questions on the One-House Veto strategy. 
<P>That is because on substance Bill Clinton won just about everything he fought for in the fiscal year 1996 budget which was finally approved by Congress. Americorps, which is a device to pay volunteers to be active in politics, supporting Clinton and his friends, is still with us. The National Endowment for the Arts, despite its subsidies for pornographic art, is in the budget. The Corporation for Public Broadcasting, despite its ability to earn billions by marketing its own products, gets subsidized for a longer term than even budgets approved by Democratic Congresses. The Legal Services Corporation, which over the years has done more harm than any other single federal program I can think of, is alive and well. Goals 2000, which is an attempt to federalize education and to impose "outcome based" methods on local school districts survived because Bill Clinton fought for it and the Republicans were unwilling to stand up and fight against it. The Commerce Department, Department of Education, and even HUD are still with us.  
<P>I could go on and on, but you get the picture. It is true that this budget does cut more money from discretionary programs than even the Republicans had proposed when they first put forth their seven-year balanced budget. So in that sense, the Republicans have a right to some credit. They are actually ahead of where they said they would be in reducing the deficit and getting the budget into balance, which is a little-known fact completely lost in the national debate.
<P>The bad news is that the federal programs the Republicans sought to kill have been funded and will be funded again in the 1997 budget. If Bill Clinton is re-elected and if the Democrats take over Congress, as well they might, these programs will grow again and be right back where they were. True, most of them have been significantly reduced under the newly-approved budget, but the bureaucrats don't care. As long as they stay alive, as long as the infrastructure stays intact, they can survive to fight another day. That is why the freshmen Republicans wanted to pull these programs up by their roots. That is why they proposed eliminating three or four cabinet departments. 
<P>I am not faulting the Republicans because these things didn't happen. The fact is that one election simply isn't enough to turn a nation around which has been heading in the opposite direction for seventy years. What the Republicans should be blamed for is not waging an all-out fight to accomplish the ends which they originally sought. In the process of such a fight they probably would have managed to get half again as much as they got. But even if they didn't, the public would understand what the 1996 election is about.
<P>Elections are best for the country when there are clear-cut differences between the parties. Now everything is fuzzed up. Both sides are claiming credit for the budget. Under these circumstances Bill Clinton and Congressional Democrats win hands down. 
<P>It was said of Bill Clinton that he didn't really believe in anything. Indeed, if you follow his rhetoric, he is masterful in appropriating the themes of his opponents. "The era of big government is over," intoned the President in his "State of the Union" speech. But Bill Clinton fought, and fought hard, for liberal federal programs. He fought on principle. He got every single thing he fought for in one way or the other. I haven't even mentioned the wholesale Republican retreat on environmental issues. 
<P>The problem here is that one side was willing to go all out to win. The other side was embarrassed by what it was fighting for. The Republicans didn't want to defend killing the Endowment for the Arts because too many upper class suburban women gave them a hard time. They didn't want to defend killing the Legal Services Corporation because they heard from too many Republican lawyers who were afraid they would get stuck with more pro-bono work. They didn't want to defend cutting off the government subsidy for PBS lest they see one more bumper sticker proclaiming that Newt killed Barney. 
<P>In short, they didn't have the stomach to face down their opponents. Bob Livingston was right. If the House had stood its ground, none of this would have happened because not a penny can be spent by a President which doesn't get money from both houses of Congress.
<P>The voters are going to take it out on the Republicans for their cowardice because it was they who built up expectations to an unreasonable level. The sad thing is that the freshmen, most of whom fought the good fight even against the wishes of their own Leadership, are likely to get hit the hardest by the voter wrath. And when that happens, the assumption will be made that cutting back federal programs is anathema with the voters and cannot be attempted again. 
<P>No Greek drama or Middles Ages morality play ever had a more tragic ending. 
<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
